AgentSudo

Target IP: 10.10.130.171
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. There is FTP, SSH, and HTTP applications open on the target machine. However, the FTP does not allow anonymous login; therefore, I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this web application displays the web page above. The source-code of this web page does not contain anything useful. However, the message above mentions to use codename as user-agent to access the site. Does it mean I have to change the User-Agent header field from the HTTP request? And can I use the codename R?


And bingo! After some experimentation by setting the User-Agent header field to R, I managed to obtain the secret site above using Burpsuite. According to the message above, apparently there are twenty-five agents in total.


I tried to check all the agents from A to Z using the same example from the previous image and obtained the useful information above. There is one agent with the name C. Setting the User-Agent header field to C allows redirection to the page agent_C_attention.php, as shown above.


The agent with the codename C's first name name is Chris, as shown above. According to the message above, apparently this user's password is weak. Maybe I can bruteforce it against the SSH and FTP applications with the username chris? There is one more agent with the codename J too.

Port 21: FTP

Now I have the username chris, I bruteforced the password crystal of this user chris using hydra as shown above. Now I have the credentials chris:crystal for the FTP application on port 21.


And using the credentials chris:credentials, I managed to successfully gain access to the FTP application. As shown above, there are three files. Using the FTP command mget *, I downloaded these files from the FTP server on my machine.


The three files are shown above. The content of the text file To_agentJ.txt is shown above. According to the message above, there is another set of credentials stored inside one of the images above.


I tried to use steghide to extract any embedded data inside the image files, but I had no luck. However, I extracted a zip file with the name 8702.zip using binwalk as shown above. This zip file contains another file called To_agentR.txt, as shown above. But it is password protected.


I used zip2john first to obtain the password hash of the zip file. Then using john, I successfully bruteforced the password alien of the zip file as shown above. Now I can extract the file To_agentR.txt using this password.


The file To_agentR.txt contains the content above. This message contains some sort of key QXJlYTUx.


I notice the key QXJlYTUx is a base64 encoded string. I obtained the plaintext Area51 after decoding it. Then using steghide with the passphrase Area51, I extracted the hidden file message.txt inside the file cute-alien.jpg as shown above. This message belongs to the agent J, aka James. It contains another password hackerrules!. Maybe this is a SSH login?

Exploitation


And bingo! Now I have a foothold on the target machine via SSH as the user James as shown above.


There is a file called Alien_autopsy.jpg at this user's home directory. I started a Python HTTP server at the user's home directory at port 8080. Then I accessed this file using my web browser. It seems to be the picture of the Roswell alien autopsy. The user_flag.txt is also located at this user's home directory.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the command above can be executed. From previous knowledge, I know this vulnerabililty can be used to elevate privileges. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2019-14287. To bypass this, the command sudo -u#-1 /bin/bash can be used.


And bingo. Now I have a root shell on the target machine by using the command sudo -u#-1 /bin/bash as shown above.
